INTRODUCTION

E-commerce (electronic commerce) is the activity of electronically buying or selling of products on online services or over the Internet. Electronic commerce draws on technologies such as mobile commerce, electronic funds transfer, supply chain management, Internet marketing, online transaction processing, electronic data interchange (EDI), inventory management systems, and automated data collection systems.(1)

In this project, we are, as a class, working with one of the highest rated e-commerce companies, namely Trendyol. Trendyol gathers the user generated data about itâs products as it is stated above in the definition of e-commerce. The products are selected from various categories and brands. Here is the eight selected products:

img1 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/products.png')
grid::grid.raster(img1)

The project is organized as a live competition, where students are expected to provide a prediction of sales per product each day. For the ease of submission, an API has been built by the staff of IE 360, to submit predictions each day. The aim of the project is to make future forecasts of eight different product sales. Accurate forecasts can help reducing the wastes by the company and it can increase the profits made from these products.

Groups are expected to submit their predictions through the provided scripts (python and r) or through the site. Groups have to provide their forecasts regularly before 13:00 every day, multiple submissions are accepted. For the daily ranking, weighted mean absolute percentage error (WMAPE) is used. Formula of the WMAPE is the following:

img2 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/wmape.png')
grid::grid.raster(img2)

Before starting to build a prediction model on the sales, the data has to be cleaned and prepared for the future works. Firstly, I have decided to seperate the products in different .csv files named with their product id. After the first look in the data set, there are lots of missing data rows. I have removed the rows with a price of -1, and I have removed the data rows with visit_count less than 10, daily. The data from 2019 years mostly have these features, price of -1 and visit_count less than 10.The row counts of data sets are different for each product since their number of missing data rows are different.

Groups are free to choose their models for prediction. As an individual, I have tried various methods to predict next dayâs sales. I have tried Simple Exponential Model, Holtâs Model, Forecasts with Different Lag Values, Linear Regression Model with Lags, and most importantly I have implemented the ARIMA model.

APPROACH

I have used several methods to forecast daily sales of the products. These methods are:

Naive Forecast

Naive forecast is the simplest version of forecasting. It is an estimating technique in which the last periodâs actuals are used as this periodâs forecast, without adjusting or manipulating them. It is mostly used as comparison tool for another forecasting methods.

For naive forecasts, I have simply set all forecasts to be the value of the last observation. That is:

img3 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/naive.png')
grid::grid.raster(img3)

Naive Forecast works best when the data follow a random walk. Since data provided by Trendyol does not follow a random walk, it did not performed well as it can be seen from the scores of daily competitions.

Simple Exponential Smoothing

Exponential smoothing is a rule of thumb technique for smoothing time series data using the exponential window function. Whereas in the simple moving average the past observations are weighted equally, exponential functions are used to assign exponentially decreasing weights over time. It is an easily learned and easily applied procedure for making predictions. Exponential smoothing is often used for analysis of time-series data.(2)

img4 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/ses.png')
grid::grid.raster(img4)

Holtâs Model

Holtâs two-parameter model, also known as linear exponential smoothing, is a popular smoothing model for forecasting data with trend. Holtâs model has three separate equations that work together to generate a final forecast. The method is also called double exponential smoothing or trend-enhanced exponential smoothing.(3) Since the data of the all products does not include an obvious trend, this model did not worked well too.

img5 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/holt.png')
grid::grid.raster(img5)

Forecasts with Lags

This method is as simple as naive forecasting. It is basically a naive forecast, but it only considers the data of n days before, where n is the lag value. The reason that I have used this method is because it is taught in the lectures of Mustafa GÃ¶kÃ§e BaydoÄan for demonstration purposes. This type of forecasting may be useful if there is obvious n-day seasonality in the data.

Linear Regression with Lagged Values

Linear regression is a linear approach to modeling the relationship between a scalar response (or dependent variable) and one or more explanatory variables (or independent variables). Since we use the linear regression with 2 days and 7 days lagged values, it can be considered as autoregressive model. This method is also taught by the instructor Mustafa GÃ¶kÃ§e BaydoÄan, in his online lectures of IE 360 Time Series Analysis.

img6 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/linear.png')
grid::grid.raster(img6)

ARIMA

In a multiple regression model, we forecast the variable of interest using a linear combination of predictors. In an autoregression model, we forecast the variable of interest using a linear combination of past values of the variable. The term autoregression indicates that it is a regression of the variable against itself.

Thus, an autoregressive model of order p can be written as:

img7 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/ar.png')
grid::grid.raster(img7)

Rather than using past values of the forecast variable in a regression, a moving average model uses past forecast errors in a regression-like model.

Thus, a moving average model of order q can be written as:

img8 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/ma.png')
grid::grid.raster(img8)

If we combine differencing with autoregression and a moving average model, we obtain a non-seasonal ARIMA model. ARIMA is an acronym for AutoRegressive Integrated Moving Average (in this context, âintegrationâ is the reverse of differencing). The full model can be written as:

img9 <- readPNG('C:/Users/ilker zeybek/Desktop/arima.png')
grid::grid.raster(img9)

Where p is the order of the autoregressive part, d is the degree of first differencing involved, and q is the order of the moving average part. This model has the highest accurracy among the all models that proposed in this section. It can be seen in the first few days of the project submission scores.(4)

RESULTS, CONCLUSIONS, AND FUTURE WORKS

Best approach to predicting the sales values was the ARIMA model since the data is complicated enough that it can not be represented as simple models that we learned through our journey. Even the ARIMA model is not enough to stay alive in the current standards of the competitive business environment. In the context of this project, ARIMA model was enough to gain good points, as it can be seen in the first few days of the submissions, but as the project progresses, I wanted to see how other models, much simpler models, can perform in this competition. As I have expected, they did not perform very well and my points were relatively lower than the other groups. As a conclusion, ARIMA model was enough to stay competitive in this project.

For the future works, we have to approach this problem like a competitive company approaches. There are many popular methods and tools that we can use for predictions and building models. Machine Learning is currently leader in this field. Any prediction based work can be easily handled with machine learning algorithms. In the current business environment, engineers must adapt to the technological changes and they have to develop themselves with the current âdata revolutionâ, or as Datacamp says in itâs advertisements, if we can not adapt the changes in the fast-paced evolving world, we will be âswept underneathâ.

mape <- function(actual,pred){
  mape <- mean(abs((actual - pred)/actual))*100
  return (mape)
}
data32939029 = read.csv("32939029.csv")
glimpse(data32939029)
set.seed(360)
ts32939029 <- ts(data32939029[, 5], start = c(2019, 11, 23), end = c(2020, 06, 12), frequency = 365)
split_data <- ts_split(ts32939029, sample.out = 75)
training32939029 <- split_data$train
test32939029 <- split_data$test
nrow(train32939029)
nrow(test32939029)
ts32939029 <- ts(train32939029[, 5], start = c(2019, 11, 23), end = c(2020, 06, 12), frequency = 365)
se_model <- ses(ts32939029, h = 1)
summary(se_model)
df_fc = as.data.frame(se_model)
test32939029$simplexp = df_fc$`Point Forecast`
mape(test32939029$sold_count, test32939029$simplexp)
holt_model <- holt(ts32939029, h = 1)
summary(holt_model)
df_holt = as.data.frame(holt_model)
test32939029$holt = df_holt$`Point Forecast`
mape(test32939029$sold_count, test32939029$holt)

summary(lr_model)
data3904356[,lr_forecast:=predict(lr_model,filtered_data)]
